commentBody:
@Ayushi Gupta 

This got mistakenly posted here. (Sorry, there is no way to delete!)



The Sound of EMUsic

@john ezra 

Oh wow I hadn't read his note.  So a form of pseudo-AI / LLM has already entered NYT Crosswords.  I guess I shouldn't be surprised, but doesn't that take all the fun and challenge out of it?  I'm quite sure a relatively primitive algorithm could regenerate tons of such iterations based on past puzzles and general LLM datasets, but I'd still rather be challenged by a clever human.

Perhaps it explains why I found almost all of the "cluing" so simple.  Dunno.  But this doesn't really bode well.  Several formerly reputable online publications have had minor scandals for publishing machine generated articles as real ones.  I naively didn't expect the NYT to join in quite yet.  :(

@Mike 
No puns -- a note worthy day!


I'll give the emus a rest.

@Crevecoeur 

Whenever I am upset about the amount of trivia in a puzzle, I ask myself, “is this really important enough to post in the comments?”

(my threshold is very high, so I’ve never actually been upset by trivia :-)

@Workingmom123 

A lot of us come here before doing Connections, so spoilers should not be posted.  If you want to discuss Connections, there is a separate column and comments section:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/04/28/crosswords/connections-companion.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2024/04/28/crosswords/connections-companion.html</a>

@Bill 

FWIW my initial entry for 19A (before the theme had become apparent) was TAILS. I also had CARRERAS at 24A, and when nothing was working out for me with those entries, I managed to rethink that area, discovering DO and TI and thus seeing the theme emerge. 

While you might be right about CRESCENDO subito, I can't recall ever seeing such an indication. Generally, there is a defined length of a crescendo, and while some are quicker than others, I would still consider them all to be gradual.

@Jack McCullough 
I won't agree that today's puzzle was 'easy', but I will agree that it was fun.  I had an average amount of 'cheats' for a Sunday (six), and an average solve time.  But I did catch onto the trick quite readily, being a fan of music.  (The rapper WIZKHALIFA was among the 'look-ups', though.)

Thank you for the BRO explanation!

@Aaron Hollon 
Correction: 

CAROM, CIERAS, BANYANS, BICORNES, SCOW, PARR. Now that is the toughest grouping I’ve seen in a very long time (including Saturdays)! TIL all of these. Oh, and HINKY/CIO was a bit cheeky as well.

@CCNY 

Your poem octave more recommendations 
(and no doubt will by end of day).

@T. Shulaise 
Yes, "sol" has an L (which is usually swallowed up by the following note "la"), but the constructor has a degree in musical education so I'm sure they are aware of that, and perhaps SO is an acceptable alternate? 

I'm no expert, just a thought...

@GRS 

Yes, same experience.

Emo/Emu

@Mean Old Lady 

I haven’t looked for an answer, but wonder sometimes about that “Flag” word being right in prime scrolling territory for righties at least…

Not suggesting anything about your experience that you describe here, just a tangential thought/inquiry.

@JohnWM 
I've hit the "flag" button by accident a number of times,  but there is a pop up window that asks for your reason for flagging. I simply close it and go about my business.

Hopefull they ignore the accidental flags.

@Grant 

RARER is a poor choice to start Wordle because you want to learn as much as you can from your first guess. You don’t need to be told three times that the answer does not have an R (which it might not). 

In other words, almost any word with five different letters is a better place to start.

@James Low 
It actually depends on who you are, where you're from, and whose book you are reading. Spelling of spoken (or in this case sung) language is often arbitrary and is subject to regional or even generational differences.
We all know SOL as a regular occurance in the NYT puzzles.  But SO is also acceptable as the fifth tone.

@Brian 

As near as I can tell, Victor BORGE has been an answer over 30 times, though most of the those appearances were over 30 years ago. 

I expect I saw him on something like The Ed Sullivan Show when I was a kid. I had no idea that he was Danish (or that his real name was Børge Rosenbaum). I probably got that answer only after getting a few crosses.

@CrispyShot,

Wow! Great tie-in to the main topic of discussion in the Comments today!




(Down, emus, down)

@Patrick J. 
They rose from bottom to top, so that means they fell from top to bottom, so SCALE DOWN and FALL TONES makes sense to me.
Also, the TONES of the SCALE really do FALL DOWN at the end of the across lines.

@RI guy
I wonder how many people doing this puzzle know the origin of the band name Steely Dan. 
I won’t give it away. It’s more fun to discover it on your own.

@Alan Parker did you write your comment after concluding that only “PAVAROTI” could possibly fit, but without having finished the puzzle?

If so, interesting move.

Otherwise, I’m not seeing where else your comment could have been coming from…

@T. Shulaise 
I gave it a pass because "Sound of Music" and "DO, a deer....SO, a needl pulling thread..."  which legitimizes that entry.

I do, however, suspect we have few to none amongst the puzzle editors and commentators who are trained musicians.  Nor are they widely read.  No gardeners.  No beekeepers for sure.  TEAZEL/TEAZLE were not permitted.  BABEL is allowed--a proper noun if ever there was--but not CELT/CELTIC.  Etc.

@dutchiris,

I don’t play Wordle all that much, but today I decided to try using RARER as a starting word. Managed to solve it in 3. 

(Enjoying my own cup of smug now)

@Helen

Ditto on all three! Plus I can never remember if SCOW is SCOW or SkOW.

cANYAN (didn't notice the lower "a") to BuNYAN (I was sure I had it!) then to google. I pretty much never google. But despite the loveliness of this puzzle, to me that zone was disharmonious. NYT editing might've been better there IMO.
